\intbl \ql \b Summary of Evaluator Report\b0 \line The evaluator indicated that Criterion 1 and 5 are in need of improvement.\line \line The BAppSocSc \'28Contact\'29 is a new qualification that SACAP intends to offer on a full-time and part-time basis at its two campuses \'28Claremont and Johannesburg\'29.  It is envisioned as a three-year degree involving three different \'E2\'80\'98streams\'E2\'80\'99\'2C or areas of specialization \'28Counselling\'2C Coaching\'2C and Management Studies\'29.  The new qualification is in line with a strategic plan to offer a \'E2\'80\'9Crange of different qualifications\'E2\'80\'9D within the broad field of applied psychology and social science.  \line \line  The evaluator argues that in terms of general conceptualization and teaching philosophy the proposed degree follows the pattern of the already accredited programmes.  It promises to blend \'E2\'80\'9Ctheory and skill-based learning\'E2\'80\'9D\'2C foster experiential learning\'2C and enhance vocational trajectories by incorporating a practical component and some work experience via placement organizations.  The planned programme comprises 43 modules\'2C ranging from NQF 5 \'289 modules\'29\'2C to NQF 6 \'2815 modules\'29 and NQF 7 \'2819 modules\'29.  Some details are given about the content of the modules in an appended document. \line \line Prescribed and recommended reading\'2C as well as learning outcomes\'2C are specified for each module.  The composition of the proposed curriculum\'2C hierarchical structure of the modules in terms of complexity \'28NQF levels\'29\'2C substantive course content\'2C and learning outcomes are all\'2C in the opinion of the evaluator\'2C aligned with what can be reasonably expected from a good quality Bachelor\'E2\'80\'99s degree in the Social Sciences.  Having said this\'2C the evaluator documents three concerns\'3A \line 1. There is some internal inconsistency in the course content because Coaching and Management Studies are defined as separate streams\'2C but considerable emphasis is placed on developing coaching and facilitation skills in the Management Studies stream \'287 of the 10 modules\'29 so that the separation between the two streams is unclear.  \line 2. The majority of the modules have a general applied psychological and counselling content. However\'2C this emphasis could also render the vertical articulation of the degree problematic\'2C particularly for students taking the Management Studies stream of the BAppSocSc.  The course designers posit that the degree will allow entry into postgraduate degrees such as Business Administration and Industrial Psychology\'2C but this appears to be optimistic and is based on assumption rather than fact.  \line \line The research component seems to be quite weak and it is unclear how students will meet the expectations about analyzing research social data which is formulated in the rationale and aims of the degree.  There is only one research-oriented module\'2C and this requires the students to write a literature review\'2C develop a research proposal\'2C and write an essay in which they review a research project.  There does not seem to be a strong focus on actually teaching students to apply quantitative or qualitative techniques\'2C and\'2For testing their ability to do this.   The programme may therefore create certain expectations in students which it cannot satisfy.  \line \line SACAP has experience in contact teaching to full-time or part-time students\'2C but as far as the evaluator could judge\'2C the BAppSocSc \'28distance\'29 is their first venture into distance teaching and the actual teaching matter content and distance learning pedagogy therefore deserves careful scrutiny. Nevertheless\'2C based on the information provided in the application and the appended documents\'2C the general approach does appear to reflect educationally sound principles and a systematic approach.  SACAP envisages a distance teaching approach for the BAppSocSc \'28distance\'29 involving virtual classrooms in the Moodle platform.  This distance tuition model adopted has not been tested before at this institution and it is therefore unclear how successfully it will run.    Launching a new degree and a new mode of delivery could be risky and could pose challenges to SACAP\'E2\'80\'99s capacity. Existing staff members \'28most of them part-time\'29 will have to be trained in distance tuition so this could also be challenging.  The prescribed and recommended reading envisaged for each module in the new degree is described in an appended document.  The choice of texts seems relevant\'2C up-to-date\'2C and of an adequate standard.  SACAP states that they have implemented an electronic learning management system \'28MySACAP\'29 to promote resource sharing and collaborative learning\'2C and also use the same system for contact teaching.  \line \line In terms of Criterion 3\'2C the evaluator noted that 26 lecturers will be involved in teaching the BAppSocSc degree.  Twenty-three of these hold a Masters or higher degree \'28the majority of these in Psychology\'29\'2C two have Honours degrees and one lecturer has a Bachelor\'E2\'80\'99s degree with a Diploma in Coaching.  The size of the staff component seems adequate\'2C and most of them have relevant qualifications and experience in tertiary education. \line \line General information is provided about assessment policies\'2C and those seem to reflect an acceptable standard in so far as formative assessment is concerned.  No specific information is provided about the summative assessment process that will be implemented for the BAppSocSc \'28contact\'29. This aspect is particularly relevant because other tertiary institutions need such information to evaluate the quality of the degree\'2C and the alignment \'28or lack thereof\'29 of the assessment processes applied at SACAP with those prevailing at other universities in South Africa. \line \line The Directorate supports the recommendation that the programme should be accredited with conditions.\line \cell \pard 

